# {{WORKER_DISPLAY_NAME}} — Linux-specific notes

The Linux-only answers from the interview, plus packaging caveats for the binary (or AppImage) build. Anything that's true regardless of OS lives in `../AUTHORING.md`; the worker's spec lives in `../WORKER.md`. This file is for the Linux-specific pieces only.

If the same worker is later built on a different OS, a sibling folder (`../windows/` or `../mac/`) gets its own `<os>-specific.md`. Those files are independent of this one — don't try to factor common bits across them.

## OS-specific interview answers

- **Host OS at forge time:** distro + version (`lsb_release -ds` or `/etc/os-release`). Glibc version matters too if it's likely to bite recipients on older distros.
- **UI framework picked on Linux:** GTK4 / Qt (native) / Electron + Tailwind / Tauri / PySide6 / Tkinter / other. Default and first-recommended is **native GTK4 or Qt against the system libs** (~5–15 MB binary — smallest deliverable and the closest match for the Claude-Code-style look on the host's chosen desktop). Offer Electron + Tailwind only if `npm` is on the `PATH` (~80–150 MB — bundles Chromium); offer Tauri only if a Rust toolchain is on the `PATH` (~5–20 MB — uses the system webview via `webkit2gtk`). Record the framework the user picked **and the size estimate they agreed to**; if they didn't take the native default, note why (headless worker that skips a GUI entirely, wanted a webview UI, preferred a Python-only stack, etc.).
- **Data location:** the actual path the worker writes to. Convention is `${XDG_DATA_HOME:-~/.local/share}/<worker-slug>/` for per-user state; deviate only when the user asked for it.
- **Scheduler glue:** none / systemd user unit in `resources/` / cron line / `.desktop` autostart entry / loops internally. If systemd, link to the unit file and note `systemctl --user enable …`.
- **Local-model runtime:** Ollama (default when the chosen model is in the Ollama library) / Hugging Face `transformers` (for Hub-only checkpoints) / LM Studio / llama.cpp / other. Note the runtime *and* the model per LOCAL unit, and whether the model is pinned at forge time or user-selectable via a GUI setting.
- **Keychain backend:** Secret Service via `keyring` (works on GNOME and KDE out of the box; headless boxes may need `gnome-keyring-daemon` or fall back to a `keyring`-supported file backend). Note which way the user wants to go.

## Packaging notes

- Default build shape: PyInstaller `--onefile` for headless workers, AppImage (wrapped around the PyInstaller output) for GUI workers.
- The display-name string with spaces becomes the binary name (`My Worker`); recipients can `chmod +x` and run directly, or you can wrap it in a `.desktop` file for menu integration.
- AppImage requires `appimagetool` on the build host. The build script checks for it and falls back to plain PyInstaller if missing — note here which path actually ran.
- Glibc symbol version is the most common "works on my machine" gotcha on Linux. Build on the oldest distro you want to support, or pin a manylinux Python in the venv.
- Anything else worth knowing for the next Linux reforge.

